Feature: a shopsystem-templates release automatically triggers a bc-base rebuild

  Closes defect (1) of lead-pwa2 — the EVENT MISMATCH — at the cross-repo
  literal. shopsystem-templates release.yml POSTs a repository_dispatch whose
  event_type is the literal string "shopsystem-templates-released" (with the
  released tag in client_payload). The prior authoring of this scenario (hash
  c179b0c448ca851c) abstracted the event_type away ("emits a
  repository_dispatch carrying the released tag"), which let bc-launcher satisfy
  the scenario by subscribing rebuild-bc-base.yml to a DIFFERENT literal
  ("templates-release") — so a real templates release stayed a silent no-op
  while the test passed. This re-sharpened scenario pins the producer-emitted
  literal explicitly: the SAME event_type string shopsystem-templates emits is
  the one shopsystem-bc-launcher must subscribe to, and only when those literals
  match does the rebuild fire. A renamed/mismatched subscription must FAIL this
  scenario. Supersedes c179b0c448ca851c. (Targets shopsystem-bc-launcher.)

  @scenario_hash:365be56194c892b9
  Scenario: a shopsystem-templates release dispatch starts a bc-base rebuild run
    Given the shopsystem-templates release workflow emits a repository_dispatch whose event_type is the literal "shopsystem-templates-released"
    And that repository_dispatch targets the shopsystem-bc-launcher repository and carries the released tag "vT_new" in its client_payload
    And the shopsystem-bc-launcher rebuild-bc-base workflow subscribes to the repository_dispatch event_type literal "shopsystem-templates-released"
    When that repository_dispatch with event_type "shopsystem-templates-released" is delivered to shopsystem-bc-launcher
    Then because the emitted event_type literal equals the subscribed event_type literal, a bc-base rebuild workflow run is started in shopsystem-bc-launcher in response to that dispatch
    And that rebuild workflow run receives the released tag "vT_new" from the dispatch client_payload
